default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhether the existing regulatory framework and Code of Practice offer adequate 
defaultprotection for the welfare of primates kept as pets and are being applied effectively
default&#xa0;
defaultMembers of the various species of non-human primates have unique and complex requirements that are integral to their welfare and well-being. Because the conditions neces
defaultsary to meet those requirements are not likely to ever be possible or feasible in captivity, particularly when these animals are kept as pets in private homes, no regulatory framework could logically be adequate or effective.
default&#xa0;
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhether people should be allo
defaultwed to keep primates as pets and, if not, how a ban might be implemented
default&#xa0;
defaultPeople should not be allowed to keep primates as pets because it is inherently a cruel practice and it is dangerous to society. Law could be written to ban any further acquisition of
default primates and to allow for re-homing of existing pets into proper sanctuaries.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe substantial negative impact caused b
defaulty trapping and removal of wild non-human primates from their natural social groups is universally recognized by relevant organizations and official bodies, for example, the International Primatological Society (
default21
default), the World Health Organization (
default38
default), Scie
defaultntific Committee on Animal Health and Animal Welfare (SCAHAW; European Union) (
default1
default), Scientific Committee on Health and Environmental Risks (SCHER) (
default34
default) and the United Kingdom Animal Procedures Committee (UKAPC) (
default19
default).
default&#xa0;
defaultBeyond the inherent negative impact of 
defaultcapture, there are the issues of the methods of capture and the transportation of the animals once captured. There has been much evidence accumulated over the years that has revealed the immense suffering that is inflicted on non-human primates during thei
defaultr capture, caging, holding and transportation to an artificial facility, whether it be breeding or research. I have evaluated this evidence and found that the conditions in which the animals have been housed at various supply and breeding facilities that e
defaultxport primates were often appalling and unacceptable, even by current standards which leave much to be desired. Many conditions breached the International Primatological Society's minimalist animal welfare guidelines.
default&#xa0;
defaultStudies have shown that transportatio
defaultn causes profound negative effects on the behavior and welfare of non-human primates (
default14,20,33
default). The animals are often packed into small wooden crates and travel as cargo. The crates are too small to permit normal postural adjustments nor any exercise. Tra
defaultnsportation to the final destination, including air and ground transit times, can take days to complete. The animals may also have to endure inadequate ventilation, noise, extreme temperature fluctuations and delays en route. Statistics for primate deaths 
defaultand illnesses either during transportation or subsequently are generally not publicized. Examples of animals found dead on arrival, often as a result of distress and shock due to the conditions on board, have been documented.
